@node OVERVIEW "Overview"
TITLE

    UltraPayAdvice 1.5a

AUTHOR

    Richard Smedley
    PO Box 59
    Sutton-In-Ashfield
    Nottinghamshire
    NG17 3HP
    England

    rsmedley@cix.compulink.co.uk

DESCRIPTION

    An intuitive & easy-to-use database, designed specifically for
    keeping a computerized record of all your payslips.

    Have you ever wondered how much of your wages actually ends up
    in the hands of the tax man? Or how much you've paid into the
    company pension scheme? This program will tell you!

    Also, by entering all your payslips into the computer, you'll
    be able to throw away all those dusty old payslips while still
    keeping a permanent record of their contents.

    Features include:

    - Intuitive & easy-to-use user interface.

    - Multiple payslip configurations, allowing you to enter payslips
      for several different people (eg. yourself & your wife)

    - All saved files are encrypted and optionally password protected
      to protect your wage details from prying eyes.

    - Graph functions.

    - Common entries, allowing you to predefine any of the details
      stored on new payslips.

    - Compatible with UltraAccounts. When you enter your payslips in
      UltraPayAdvice, the program automatically enters them into your
      accounts for you.

NEW FEATURES

    - Graphs can now be printed.

    - Minor bug fixes & enhancements.


SPECIAL REQUIREMENTS

    - Requires: AmigaOS 2.0, 1 meg ram, reqtools.library (supplied)

    - Recommended: AmigaOS 3.0, hard drive, additional memory

AVAILABILITY

    Available via FTP from Aminet sites.
    ftp://wuarchive.wustl.edu/pub/aminet/biz/misc/ultrapay.lha

PRICE

    The unregistered version is fully functional, but will display
    shareware reminders from time to time.

    Registration fee is 5 Pounds Sterling (or equivalent)

DISTRIBUTABILITY

    Shareware, unregistered copies are freely distributable.

    UltraPayAdvice is (C) Richard Smedley 1997
@endnode

------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node REQUIRED "Requirements & Tooltypes"
REQUIREMENTS
------------

Requires at least Kickstart 2.0 or better, and ideally at least 1.5 meg of
memory (1 meg machines will probably run out of memory after you've started
entering quite a few payslips). A hard drive isn't essential, but would
also be recommended.

Hard drive installation is simply a matter of dragging the PayAdvice drawer
to an appropriate place on your hard drive. Registered users need to make
sure that their keyfile is in the same drawer as the program itself!

PayAdvice uses reqtools.library by Nico François & Magnus Holmgren.



TOOLTYPES
---------

You can set the following tooltypes in the PayAdvice program icon:

    DEFAULTFILE=<filename>
        The file "<filename>" will be automatically loaded for you each
        time you use the program - remember to include the full path if
        it isn't in the PayAdvice drawer! You'll still need to type the
        password (if you've used one) but it'll save you from having to
        use the file requester every time...

    SCREENMODE=CUSTOM or WORKBENCH
        Select whether PayAdvice should use the Workbench screen or its
        own custom screen. This can also be changed by selecting one of
        the options from the "Options/Screen mode" menu in the program.

    BACKUPS=NO
        When you save your file PayAdvice normally renames the previous
        file and keeps it as a backup copy, just in case something goes
        wrong corrupting your data. Selecting this will *prevent* these
        backups from being made.
@endnode

------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node START "Getting started"
GETTING STARTED
---------------

Just double-click on the icon to load PayAdvice, and the main PayAdvice
window will appear.

The PayAdvice window itself simply consists of a list which displays a
brief summary of all the payslips that you've entered into the program,
together with a button for entering new payslips.

The first thing that you'll need to do is configure the program to deal
with the particular combination of additions & deductions that appear on
*your* payslips. This is done automatically the first time you enter a
payslip, but if you prefer to do it manually then all you have to so is
select "Edit/Wage titles" from the menu in the PayAdvice window.

                      @{" Manually configuring the program " link CONFIG}

Then, whenever you or your partner receives a new payslip, all you have to
do is press the "New entry" button at the bottom of the window. A list will
appear for you to select whose wages your entering. Select the appropriate
name in the list, and a calendar will then appear for you to enter the date
of the new payslip. After you've entered a date, the payslip window itself
will appear: If you look at the box at the bottom of the window, you'll see
that the name of your first addition has been displayed. Just type in the
amount of that addition, and press the return key - your next addition (or
deduction) will then appear, and so on until everything has been entered.
If you ever need to go back and change one of the amounts that you've typed
in, the just use the mouse to select that addition/deduction from the list.
After you've finished entering everything, press the "OK" button to store
the details.

You can edit (or erase) a payslip by simply clicking on its entry in the
list in the main PayAdvice window. The payslip window will then appear,
where you can edit any of the details by clicking on the appropriate entry
in the list. Pressing the "Erase" button will erase that payslip from your
file, and the "Print" button can be used to make a printout of the details
for that particular payslip.

There's also a number of pull down menu's available:

                               @{" Menu functions " link MENUS}
@endnode

------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node SAVING "Saving your payslip file"
SAVING YOUR PAYSLIP FILE
------------------------

Since all financial details are confidential, UltraPayAdvice always saves
everything in an encrypted & password-protected format, preventing anyone
else from being able to read through your financial affairs. The password
protection is actually optional, your file will still be encrypted even if
you choose not to use a password - but, without a password, anyone who can
load UltrapayAdvice will also be able to load your payslip file.

For those who are interested, UltraPayAdvuce saves all its files using a
filename extension of ".pay" - don't worry if you don't understand quite
what this means, because it'll be done for you automatically!

When you save your file, selecting "Project/Save" from the menu will save
your file using the current filename and password, to save you from having
to go through the file & password requesters. Selecting "Project/Save as"
will prompt you for both a filename and a password.

The passwords can be up to ten letters long, and you can literally use
absolutely anything you want as your password - your wifes name, her bra
size, anything at all! The point is that you should use something that'll
be easy for you to remember, but which nobody else will ever be able to
guess. The only thing to remember is that passwords ARE case sensitive, so
"a" is different to "A" - be careful not to get muddled up if you use any
capital letters in your password.

If you don't want to use any password at all, then just press the return
key without typing anything when asked to enter a password. Your file will
still be encrypted, but you won't be asked to enter a password before being
allowed to load the file in. If you've saved your file without a password,
then you can easily add a password later by using the "Save as" menu item
and entering your new password at the prompt.

Whenever you type your password in, you'll notice that a "*" is displayed
on the screen for each character of your password - this is to stop anyone
from reading your password on the screen while you type it in. Because you
can't see the password on the screen, when you enter a new password you'll
be asked to type it in a second time to confirm that you didn't make any
typing mistakes the first time you entered it - a warning will be displayed
if you don't enter exactly the same text both times.
@endnode

------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CONFIG "Configuring the wage categories"
CONFIGURING THE WAGE CATEGORIES
-------------------------------

As you know, all wage packets consist of numerous additions and deductions
to your earnings, such as basic pay, overtime and tax - but the actual
combinations of those individual additions & deductions can vary wildly
from one person to another.

This program can handle several different payslip configurations at the
same time, making it ideal for entering both you and your partners wage
details in the same payslip file. Each separate payslip configuration can
consist of up to eighteen additions and eighteen deductions, which should
be more than enough for most people!

There are two ways of setting up a new wage category...

Firstly, the automatic way: When you press the "New entry" button in the
main PayAdvice window, a window pops up asking you to select a category for
the new payslip. Normally, you'd just select "My payslips" (or whatever!)
to use that particular configuration, but if you instead press the "Create"
button then the configuration window will appear for you to enter all the
details for the new category.

The second way of doing it is to simply select "Edit/Wage titles" from the
menu in the PayAdvice window. Clicking on either an existing category (or
the "Create" button) will display the configuration window, where you can
enter/edit all the appropriate information.

Either way, all you have to do is type the names of all those individual
additions & deductions into the on-screen boxes - for example, you might
put "Basic pay" in the first additions-box, and "Overtime" in the second,
and so forth. Pressing the cycle-gadget at the bottom of the window will
cycle the display between your additions & deductions.

Incidentally, you don't need to worry about any of the totals (e.g. total
gross, or total deductions) while entering the names of all your additions
and deductions - these are automatically created and dealt with by the
program itself!

You'll notice that the "UltraAccounts a/c" and "Tag" buttons at the top of
the window can't be used: These buttons are only available to UltraAccounts
users who are using PayAdvice to enter their payslips in their accounts
(they're actually used for selecting which account & tag to use for your
payslips when the program automatically enters them in UltraAccounts - and
hence they can only be used when this window is called up from within the
UltraAccounts program, rather than from PayAdvice)

Pressing the "Edit personal details" button will display a second window,
where you can enter some personal details about yourself. Here, there are
boxes for you to enter your name, your department, your clock number (if
you use a clocking-on system), and of course your employer. These details
are all entirely optional - you *don't* have to enter them to be able to
use the program! The only difference that it makes is that, if you enter
them, then this information will also be included on any printouts that you
make.
@endnode

------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node COMMON "Common entries"
COMMON ENTRIES
--------------

If you're paid a fixed salary rather than an hourly rate (for example) then
it's quite possible that some of your additions or deductions will always
have exactly the same value week-after-week, month-after-month. Instead of
having to continually re-type exactly the same information everytime you
enter a new payslip, you can predefine these common entries and have the
program enter them for you.

Select "Edit/Common entries" from the menu in the PayAdvice window, and
then select the appropriate wage category.

A window will appear showing the names of all the additions and deductions
to your wages (use the cycle-gadget to switch the display between additions
and deductions). To predefine a value for any of your payslip entries, all
you have to do is enter the required amount in the appropriate box.

Then, each time you enter a new payslip, that amount will automatically be
entered for you for that particular addition/deduction - saving you from
having to type it in yourself.
@endnode

